'''David Brian Dougherty''' (1967 – 20 April 2017) was a New Zealander who was convicted in 1993 on charges of [[Child abduction|abduction]] and the [[rape]] of an 11-year-old girl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/view/news_national_story_skin/47392|title=Apology and money for Dougherty}}</ref> In 1997, when new [[DNA evidence]] ruled him out of the charge, Dougherty was [[Acquittal|acquitted]] after serving over three years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sunday-star-times/features/1387410/Falsely-imprisoned-David-Doughertys-story|title=Falsely imprisoned: David Dougherty's story}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/HL0908/S00125.htm|title=Forensic Science}}</ref> He received a public apology in 2001 along with $868,728 in compensation.<ref>{{cite web|title=David Dougherty - Locked up in a nightmare|url=http://www.peterellis.org.nz/FalseAllegations/2001-0713_Herald_DavidDoughertyLockedUpInANightmare.htm|author=Catherine Masters|year=2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=3504996|title=10 years of guilt over for rape victim | work=The New Zealand Herald | date=31 May 2003}}</ref> In 2003, the real offender, Nicholas Reekie, was found guilty and convicted of the crime.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=3524028|title=Apology but no compensation for rape victim | work=The New Zealand Herald | date=18 September 2003}}</ref>  Dougherty's case was the subject of the 2008 [[New Zealand]] telemovie ''Until Proven Innocent'' which documents the [[miscarriage of justice]] that had Dougherty imprisoned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kiwicrime.blogspot.com/2009/08/dvd-review-until-proven-innocent-david.html|title=DVD Review: Until Proven Innocent}}</ref>

In November 2010, Dougherty pleaded guilty to a [[burglary]] charge. He admitted going to a [[Palmerston North]] property in October that year to collect money he was owed. He smashed open a ranch slider door and stole beer and [[DVD-Video|DVDs]] before being caught by the home owner. He claimed he did not realise the previous owner had moved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/david-dougherty-pleads-guilty-burglary-3909138|title=David Dougherty pleads guilty to burglary}}</ref> Dougherty was meant to face court on [[theft]] and burglary charges in May 2011, but instead was arrested shortly before his case was called and sentencing did not go ahead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arrest Interrupts Sentencing|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10728300 | work=The New Zealand Herald | date=27 May 2011}}</ref> He was ordered by the court to undergo a drug and alcohol assessment.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man falsely accused of rape remanded on burglary charges|url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/rape-falsely-accused-remanded-burglary-charges-4190065}}</ref> On 7 July 2011 Dougherty was sentenced to 300 hours of [[Community_work#Alternative_sentencing|community work]] and nine months of supervision.<ref name=rollercoaster>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/5255113/Rollercoaster-Dougherty-gets-to-go-home |title='Rollercoaster' Dougherty gets to go home |author=Ellingham, Jimmy |date=8 July 2011 |work=[[Manawatu Standard]] |accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref>

Dougherty died on 20 April 2017, not long after his 50th birthday, after a long illness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/92036244/man-who-was-wrongly-convicted-of-rape-and-abduction-dies-after-long-illness|accessdate=28 April 2017|title=Man who was wrongly convicted of rape and abduction dies after long illness|date=28 April 2017|publisher=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11847308|accessdate=28 April 2017|title=David Dougherty, who was wrongly convicted of rape and abduction, dies of cancer at age 50|date=28 April 2017|publisher=NZ Herald}}</ref>

