{{EngvarB|date=October 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Edward Pritchard Gee | image = | caption = | birth_date = 1904 | birth_place = [[County Durham]], United Kingdom<ref name=V65>Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society, Vol. 65 (1969) - [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&safe=off&client=safari&rls=en&q=%22Immanuel%20College%22%20Edward%20Pritchard%20Gee&um=1&ie=UTF-8&sa=N&tab=wp Item Notes], Page 361</ref> | death_date = 1968 | death_place = | residence = [[Assam]], India | nationality = British | alma_mater = [[Durham School]] and [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]]<ref name=V65/> | other_names = | known_for = discovery of [[Gee's golden langur]], promoting creation of [[Chitwan National Park]] | occupation = [[Assam tea|Tea planter]] | title = | children = | footnotes = Gee was described as: "a fairly built heavy man, balding and wears tortoise shell glasses. He repeats everything twice over, the second phrase tumbling out after the first."<ref name="Rangarajan"/>}} '''Edward Pritchard Gee''' (1904–1968) was a [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] educated, [[Anglo-Indian]]<ref name="Groves">{{cite book|last=Groves|first=Colin P.|title=Horses, Asses and Zebras in the Wild |publisher=Newton Abbot|location=England|year=1974|pages=105|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8aI_AAAAYAAJ&q=%22E+P+Gee%22+%22anglo+indian%22+-com&dq=%22E+P+Gee%22+%22anglo+indian%22+-com&ei=MYVCS-DnNqbAzQT24-nfDQ&cd=1}}</ref> tea-planter and an amateur [[naturalist]] in [[Assam]], [[India]]. He is credited with the 1953 discovery of [[Gee's golden langur]]. He is notable as an early influential [[wildlife conservation]]ist, especially for his 1959 and 1963 surveys and recommendations resulting in the creation of [[Chitwan National Park]], the first of [[Protected areas of Nepal#National parks|nine national parks]] in [[Nepal]].
==Conservationist== Gee was the fourth son of Rev. C. G. Gee, Vicar of Lowick and his wife, daughter of a Colonel Briggs of Hylton Castle.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty years in Ministry | page=4| newspaper=The Berwick Advertiser| date=21 January 1937|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000717/19370121/102/0004| via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]| subscription=yes}}</ref> As a tea planter, Gee was part of a highly influential group of British landowners very close to the highest levels of provincial power. Soon after [[Independence Day (India)|India's Independence]], Gee was one of the first to assess the threats to [[endangered species]] and outline [[Wildlife conservation|conservation]] measures to protect them. He believed cattle had no place in a sanctuary and thought they would arouse a sense of surprise, disappointment, and revulsion in tourists who had come looking for wild animals. [[File:Golden Langur.jpg|thumb|[[Gee's golden langur]] named for E.P. Gee]] Like his contemporaries, [[Salim Ali]] and [[M. Krishnan]], Gee was a non-official member of the Indian Board for Wildlife, the apex body that advises the Union Government on wildlife matters. Gee argued in favour of separate [[Deputy Conservator of Forests (India)|wildlife wardens]] within the Forest Department, who have specific powers in relation to fauna. He wrote extensively on the role of [[forester]]s as protectors of wildlife, as he thought it important to rely on their goodwill. He believed conservation success depended on cooperation between foresters and the forest ministers of each state and that the role of the central government was only to advise and assist.<ref name="Rangarajan"/>
He is famous for his discovery of the langur species which is named after him, [[Gee's golden langur]].{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} He had heard reports of an unusual coloured primate and he organised an expedition in 1953. He managed to film the langurs near the [[Sankosh River]] on the border between [[Assam]] and [[Bhutan]].{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} [[File:Rhinos leofleck.jpg|thumb|Elephant safari in Chitwan National Park]] He recommended that the [[Govindgarh, Madhya Pradesh|Govindgarh Palace]] of the Maharaja of [[Rewa (princely state)|Rewa]], and its [[white tiger]] inhabitants, be made a "National Trust", which didn't happen. [[File:Kazi rhino edit.jpg|thumb|[[Indian rhinoceros|Great Indian one-horned rhinoceros]] at Kaziranga National Park]] In 1959, the [[Fauna and Flora International|Fauna Preservation Society]] appointed E.P. Gee to undertake a survey of the [[Chitwan Valley]]. Gee, who had spent most of his life in India and was an authority on its wildlife, recommended creation of a national park north of the [[East Rapti River|Rapti River]].<ref name="Adventures"/> He also proposed creation of a wildlife sanctuary south of the river for a trial period of ten years. In 1963, after he surveyed Chitwan again, this time for both the Fauna Preservation Society and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]], Gee recommended extension of the national park to [[Indian rhinoceros|rhinoceros]] areas to the south of the river. In December 1970, His Majesty [[King Mahendra]] approved extension of the national park as recommended, thus creating the first national park in [[Nepal]].<ref name="Adventures">{{cite web|url=http://www.adventuresnepal.com/nepal/chitwan_national_park/establishment.htm|title=Establishment-Chitwan National Park|year=2009|publisher=Adventures Nepal|accessdate=3 January 2010}}</ref>
After retirement from tea planting in Assam, Gee settled in [[Shillong]], where he assembled one of the finest private [[orchid]] collections.<ref name="ali">{{cite book|last=Ali|first=Sálim |title=The fall of a Sparrow |publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Delhi |year=1985|pages=189|isbn= 0-19-568747-7 }}</ref> After Independence, sensitive to the nationalism of the new Indian leadership, Gee searched for and emphasized indigenous nature conservation practices, ranging from ancient imperial edicts to village traditions of protecting nesting bird colonies. This cooperative and culturally sensitive style won recognition from [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] whom Gee accompanied together with Nehru's daughter [[Indira Gandhi]] and son-in-law [[Feroze Gandhi]] on a tour of [[Kaziranga National Park|Kaziranga Wildlife Sanctuary]] on 20 October 1956.<ref name="AMTRON">{{cite web|url=http://assamforest.in/knp-osc/linkpages.php?u=vww|title=Visitors Who's who, Guest Register 1938 to 1958, Kaziranga Game Sanctuary| last=Official Support Committee|first=Kaziranga National Park|year=2009|publisher=AMTRON|accessdate=4 January 2010|location=Assam}}</ref> Nehru's forward to Gee's book in February 1964 was one of the only pieces he ever wrote on wildlife conservation. In it he said, {{quotation|Life would become very dull and colourless if it did not have these magnificent animals and birds to look at and to play with.}}
Nehru called for more refuges for vanishing wildlife, but he died in May and Gee died four years later. It was the end of an era.<ref name="Rangarajan"/>
==Publications== [[File:E.P.Gee Wildlife cover.jpg|thumb|''The Wildlife of India'', 1964 first edition]] *E.P. Gee was an active contributor to the early wildlife protection policy of India. He wrote his own account of his wildlife work in the book ''Wildlife of India'' in 1964. This work makes a good comparison with present-day [[wildlife conservation]] efforts in India.<ref name="gee">{{cite book|last=Gee|first=Edward Prichard|title=The Wildlife of India|publisher=Fontana |location=London |year=1964 |edition=orig. publ., paperback ed., 1969, (also: Indus, 1992, repr., Harper Collins, New Delhi 2000|pages=224, ills., foreword by [[Jawaharlal Nehru]]|isbn=81-7223-406-6|url=http://indianmedicine.eldoc.ub.rug.nl/root/G/30459/?pFullItemRecord=ON}}</ref>
:The [[India]]n [[Minister of State|Minister of State (Independent Charge)]] for [[Ministry of Environment and Forests (India)|Environment and Forests]] since May, 2009, [[Jairam Ramesh]]'s acquaintance with the natural world began when he was nine (1963) and was gifted ''The Wildlife of India''. The book is a classic with a beautiful foreword by [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] that has stayed with him all these years.<ref name="Churumuri">{{cite web|url=http://churumuri.wordpress.com/2009/07/19/18-things-you-might-like-to-know-about-jairam/|title=18 things you might like to know about Jairam|last= Churumuri|date=2009-07-19|publisher=Wordpress.com|accessdate=29 December 2009}}</ref>
:''Wildlife in India'' was first published in hard cover 224 page, 8 b/w and 12 colour plates illustrated edition, weight 645 grams by [[HarperCollins|William Collins, Sons and Co Ltd]] in London in July 1964 (Second hardback edition. green cloth. 192pp; 12 colour plates 64 b/w plates.) and [[E.P. Dutton & Co.]] 6 1/8" x 9", Green hardback with gold print on black background on spine, 192 pages, 8vo. Illus. with 8 b/w and 12 colour plates) in New York in December 1964. Third impression in March, 1965 had 192 pages with 12 colour and over 60 b/w illustrations. The book was republished by Fontana paperbacks in London in 1969 and again in 177 page version on 1 May 1992 by Indus, South Asia Books. It was reprinted by [[HarperCollins|Harper Collins]] in New Delhi in 2000.<ref name="gee"/>
:Book review by India Club says, [[File:E.P.Gee Wildlife cover3.jpg|thumb|upright|"The Wildlife of India, 2000 edition]] {{quotation|For anyone interested in wildlife or the natural resources of India this is an enthralling and informative book. For the animals themselves it may make all the difference between extermination and survival. Some of the noblest and most beautiful animals in the world are to be found in India. But they are unlikely to survive outside the pages of Kipling and the memoirs of big-game hunters unless something is done quickly to save them. E P Gee has spent half a lifetime studying and photographing animals and birds in India. He has sat in the open within ten feet of a lion, has fallen in front of a charging rhinoceros and he has a strange tale to tell of a bird mystery in Assam; but although it is full of good stories this is not a book of daring deeds. It is a unique panorama of the wildlife resources of India, her sanctuaries, the animals which inhabit them and the men who have done most to preserve them.}}
{{quotation|COMMENTS: Absolutely splendid. The photographs and text are of a very high quality. - [[Peter Scott]] - The author's great experience of Indian wildlife and his superb photography render this one of the most enthralling books on natural history. All interested in nature will find it hard to stop reading. - [[The American Naturalist|The Naturalist]] - A plea for the preservation of wild animals and birds in India. Mr. Gee a splendid raconteur, takes each of the main species and discusses with a wealth of anecdotes its chances of survival. A dedicated man, he is no fanatic. Of outstanding interest.<ref name="marelibri">{{cite web|url=http://www.marelibri.com/search/current?maximumPrice=0&keywords=&firstResult=0&ISBN=&selectedDatasources=511&quicksearch=&matchTypeList=ALL&author=&title=the+wild+life+of+india&description=&minimumPrice=0&sorting=RELEVANCE&booksellerName=&keycodes=&cid=3353187|title= the wild life of india|work=Search -|publisher=marelibri|accessdate=3 January 2010}}</ref> }}
